        "text": "2 Chronicles 7:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and elsewhere. Older expositors (Clericus, J. H. Mich.), referring to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 15:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", understand בהלּל ויּענוּ of the alternative singing of two choirs, one of which sang, \"Praise the Lord, for He is good;\" and the other responded, \"And His mercy endureth for ever.\" In the present passage, however, there is no decided allusion to responsive singing; hence (with Bertheau) we take יענוּ in the sense of, \"They sang to the Lord with hymns of thanksgiving.\" Probably they sang such songs as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 106-107",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 118",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which commence with an invitation to praise the Lord because He is good, etc. All the people, moreover, raised a loud shout of joy. גּדולה תּרוּעה is repeated in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 3:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
